Tidak seperti mata uang pada umumnya, bitcoin tidak tergantung dengan mempercayai penerbit utama. Bitcoin menggunakan sebuah database yang didistribusikan dan menyebar ke node-node dari sebuah jaringan P2P ke jurnal transaksi, dan menggunakan kriptografi untuk menyediakan fungsi-fungsi keamanan dasar, seperti memastikan bahwa bitcoin-bitcoin hanya dapat dihabiskan oleh orang memilikinya, dan tidak pernah boleh dilakukan lebih dari satu kali.

Lesson Objectives

By the end of this lesson, students will be able to:

Define conditional sentences.

Identify and differentiate between the four types of conditional sentences (0, 1, 2, and 3).

Use conditional sentences correctly in writing and speaking.



Definition of Conditional Sentences

Conditional sentences are sentences that describe a condition and its possible result. They usually consist of two clauses:

1. The "if" clause ‚Üí Expresses the condition.


2. The main clause ‚Üí Expresses the result.



Example:
‚úÖ If you eat too much, you will feel sick.

Each type of conditional sentence expresses a different degree of possibility or reality.


Kinds of Conditional Sentences

1. Zero Conditional (Type 0) ‚Äì General Truths & Facts

Structure:

If + present simple, present simple

Usage:

Used to express general truths, scientific facts, or things that always happen.


Examples:

‚úÖ If you heat ice, it melts.
‚úÖ If you mix red and blue, you get purple.
‚úÖ If people don‚Äôt drink water, they die.

2. First Conditional (Type 1) ‚Äì Real Future Situations

Structure:

If + present simple, will + base verb

Usage:

Used to talk about possible future events that are likely to happen if the condition is met.


Examples:

‚úÖ If you study, you will pass the test.
‚úÖ If it rains tomorrow, we will stay at home.
‚úÖ If she calls me, I will answer.


3. Second Conditional (Type 2) ‚Äì Hypothetical Present/Future

Structure:

If + past simple, would + base verb

Usage:

Used to talk about imaginary or unlikely situations in the present or future.


Examples:

‚úÖ If I were a millionaire, I would buy a big house.
‚úÖ If she studied harder, she would get better grades.
‚úÖ If we had more time, we would travel more.

(Note: ‚ÄúWere‚Äù is used instead of ‚Äúwas‚Äù in formal English for all subjects.)


4. Third Conditional (Type 3) ‚Äì Past Hypotheticals

Structure:

If + past perfect, would have + past participle

Usage:

Used to talk about unreal situations in the past (things that didn‚Äôt happen).
